Introduction

The Basics on LA and Crime

The city of Los Angeles is one of the largest metropolitan areas in the United States and is the most populous city in the state of California with a population of nearly 3.9 million people. Unsurprisingly, with such a dense urban population, there are many, many crimes committed on a daily basis. These crimes range greatly in severity and scale, from offenses as minor as jaywalking and trespassing, to crimes as severe as murder, arson, and rape. The city of Los Angeles and its police department work to identify, address, and prevent crime in all of the 21 neighborhoods within the city limits.

Goal

As part of these efforts to keep the public informed and increase accountability, the LAPD collects and publishes crime data on a regular basis. The subject of this machine learning project will be the 2020 to 2024 Los Angeles crime data. This dataset contains a variety of information on every crime committed in Los Angeles during this four year period. The goal of this project will be to predict the classiffication of a crime according to a pre-defined scale of severity. While there is a current system of classification for crimes, I hope to train a machine learning model to predict the classification of crimes in a manner that could prove more useful for proactive identification and response to offenses being actively perpetrated.

The Current System

Currently, the classification of crimes in this dataset is in accordance with the 2019 FBI Uniform Crime Reporting(UCR) program. The UCR program classifies crimes as either Part I or Part II, based on their severity and rate of occurrence nation-wide.

For Part I offenses, the FBI collects monthly reports from participating law enforcement across the country that contain the number of Part I offenses that are newly known to them, which of these offenses have been cleared by arrest or exceptional means(FBI.gov), as well as the age, sex, and race of those who have been arrested for committing any of these offenses. Part I crimes are:

  • CRIMINAL HOMICIDE
  • FORCIBLE RAPE
  • ROBBERY
  • AGGRAVATED ASSAULT
  • BURGLARY
  • LARCENY THEFT
  • MOTOR VEHICLE THEFT
  • ARSON
  • HUMAN TRAFFICKING, COMMERCIAL SEX ACTS
  • HUMAN TRAFFICKING, INVOLUNTARY SERVITUDE

Per the UCR webpage on the FBI website, the purpose of the reporting of Part I offenses and information concerning them is:

The UCR Program collects data about Part I offenses in order to measure the level and scope of crime occurring throughout the nation. The programs founders chose these offenses because they are serious crimes, they occur with regularity in all areas of the country, and they are likely to be reported to the police.

For Part 2 offenses, law enforcement agencies participating in the UCR program only provide the FBI with a monthly report containing arrest data on these crimes. Part II crimes are:

  • OTHER ASSAULTS (SIMPLE)
  • FORGERY AND COUNTERFEITING
  • FRAUD
  • EMBEZZLEMENT
  • STOLEN PROPERTY: BUYING, RECEIVING, POSSESSING
  • VANDALISM
  • WEAPONS: CARRYING, POSSESSING, ETC.
  • PROSTITUTION AND COMMERCIALIZED VICE
  • SEX OFFENSES (EXCEPT RAPE, PROSTITUTION, AND COMMERCIALIZED VICE)
  • DRUG ABUSE VIOLATIONS
  • GAMBLING
  • OFFENSES AGAINST THE FAMILY AND CHILDREN
  • DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE
  • LIQUOR LAWS
  • DRUNKENNESS
  • DISORDERLY CONDUCT
  • VAGRANCY
  • ALL OTHER OFFENSES
  • SUSPICION
  • CURFEW AND LOITERING LAWS (PERSONS UNDER 18)

This is only a list of the offenses categorized by their respective Part designation. A detailed explanation of the offenses listed above can be found at the following link:

https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s/2019/crime-in-the-u.s.-2019/topic-pages/offense-definitions

An Alternate Approach

While there is nothing inherently wrong with the FBIs UCR program, it is mostly focused on the retrospective collection of data on crimes that have been designated as frequent and severe on a national scale. While this data could be very useful for decision-making regarding national law-enforcement policies and directives, it seems less useful on a more local, immediate scale.

I would like to impose a different structure for classification; a four level scale with level 1 indicating minimal severity (response time can be diminished, with more severe crimes addressed first) and level 4 indicating a violent crime with high probability of lethality (response time must be as short as physically possible).

Let the proposed scale be as follows:

  1. Low Severity (Lowest Severity) - Offenses include minor, non-violent misdemeanors such as vandalism, petty theft, and trespassing.

  2. Moderate Severity - Offenses include more serious misdemeanors and property-related crimes, such as non-violent burglary, grand theft, and identity theft.

  3. High Severity - Offenses include non-lethal violent crimes, such as assault, battery, or unarmed robbery.

  4. Extreme Severity (Highest Severity) - Offenses include serious, violent crimes with a high plausibility of lethality. All sexual crimes will also be classified as severity 4. Examples of offenses include homicide, rape, armed robbery, and aggravated assault.

Ideally, the prospective model will be able to correctly classify crimes with their appropriate level of severity. A reasonably accurate model could prove useful for responding to new, in-progress crimes that require attention from Los Angeles police officers. The ability to designate and order crimes with regard to their severity could help with the priority of where nearby units are dispatched to first, hopefully saving lives in the process.

Data Citation

The source of this data is the Los Angeles Police Department. It is publically available on the City of Los Angeles website. The downloadable version of this data can be found at this link:

https://data.lacity.org/Public-Safety/Crime-Data-from-2020-to-Present/2nrs-mtv8/about_data

The official dataset description found on the City of LA website is:

This dataset reflects incidents of crime in the City of Los Angeles dating back to 2020. This data is transcribed from original crime reports that are typed on paper and therefore there may be some inaccuracies within the data. Some location fields with missing data are noted as (0, 0). Address fields are only provided to the nearest hundred block in order to maintain privacy. This data is as accurate as the data in the database. Please note questions or concerns in the comments.

This data is updated on a bi-monthly basis to include the most recent possible information on crimes committed in Los Angeles. I updated my downloaded dataset with the most recent version on September 11th, 2024, to find that there are now 974,477 observations. In a 26 day period, there were 7,526 additional crimes committed!

Reducing Size

Firstly, let us tackle the issue of this datasets magnitude. We have 974,477 observations, with 28 variables for each observation. Lets reduce the size of our dataset.

My initial approach to reducing the size of the dataset was to select the three neighborhoods with the highest total crime count over the four year period for which the LAPDcrimedata dataset accounts for. This seems like an okay idea at first, but later it seemed damaging, as I could not use geographic predictors very well, as there was not a ton of variation in geographic area. Additionally, taking the top three neighborhoods for crime count still leaves us with somewhere in the neighborhood of 185,000 observations.

Instead of choosing the top three neighborhoods, lets take a random sample of 1000 observations from each of the 21 neighborhoods in the LA City limits. By doing this, we get a wider range of observations throughout the city. Not only will this result in a smaller dataset than taking just the three neighborhoods with the most crime, it should make our results later on more generally applicable.

LA_crime_subset <- LAPDcrimedata %>% 
  group_by(AREA.NAME) %>% 
  slice_sample(n=1000) %>% 
  ungroup()

counts_by_area <- LA_crime_subset %>%
  group_by(AREA.NAME) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(count))
print(counts_by_area)

From the codebook, we can notice that there are some variables that can likely be removed off-the-bat, as they either contain information that is not useful for our model, or duplicate information that makes it redundant to use both variables with this information.

Additionally, some variables are there primarily for human-interpretability. We can use these variables to understand our observations better, but they will not provide any meaningful input to the model, as they are character strings. We can keep these variables in the larger LAPDcrimedata dataset, but they are not necessary in LA_crime_subset which we will be using for our modeling process.

Lets identify those variables:

  1. DR_NO - Contains a division of records number, not useful for modeling.
  2. Status - Contains status code, where most observations are IC. We are not concerned with whether a case has been resolved or not.
  3. Status Desc - Describes status code, not useful.
  4. Crm.Cd.1 - Lists the code of the primary offense being created. Redundant because Crm.Cd contains the same info (additional reasoning for using Crm.Cd instead provided later)
  5. Crm.Cd.Desc - Contains a character string to describe the code contained in Crm.Cd and Crd.Cd.1. Not useful for modeling.
  6. Premis.Desc - Contains a character string to describe the code contained in Premis.Cd. Not useful for modeling
  7. Date.Rptd - Contains a DD/MM/YYYY date value for when an observation of crime was reported. Not useful for our purposes
  8. Mocodes - Contains one or multiple codes that refer to specific characteristics of a crime. While this could prove useful if there was only one per observation or they were easily distinguishable, many observations have multiple codes and they are mushed into the Mocodes variable together. Additionally, there are 4,000+ distinct Mocodes and many of them describe characteristics that would not be productive to our modeling process

Lets remove these variables:

LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  select(-DR_NO,-Status,-Status.Desc,-Crm.Cd.1,-Crm.Cd.Desc,-Premis.Desc,-Date.Rptd,-Mocodes)

While I suspect that some of the other variables will be able to be removed later, there is a chance some introduce meaningful additions to our model. as a result, I will keep the remaining variables, at least through our EDA section.

While its only a small reduction in dimensionality, we now have 21 variables, rather than 28. An improvement!

Handling Missing Data

When we first loaded and summarized our dataset, we saw that some variables had missing entries for some observations. Recall that these variables and the number of missing entries per were:

  1. Premis.Cd (14 missing)
  • We may not have to handle missing Premis.Cd values. Lets see if the smaller LA_crime_subset dataset has any missing values for this variable:
sum(is.na(LA_crime_subset$Premis.Cd))
## [1] 0

There are no missing values, which means we dont need to take any further action.

  1. Weapon.Used.Cd(648,695 missing)
  • To handle missing values for Weapon.Used.Cd I believe it is most appropriate to feature-engineer a new variable, Weapon.Used. This is because, regardless of what weapon is used, the fact that any weapon is employed almost guarantees that a crime will be of a high severity value according to the scale we have designated. Lets create this new variable and remove the old variable. Additionally, since we are not interested in what kind of weapon was used, we can also remove the WeaponDesc variable:
LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  mutate(Weapon.Used = ifelse(is.na(Weapon.Used.Cd),0,1)) %>% 
  select(-Weapon.Used.Cd,-Weapon.Desc)
  1. Crm.Cd.1(11 missing)
  • We have already handled missing values for Crm.Cd.1 by removing it from our smaller LA_crime_subset dataset. This should not introduce bias and/or inaccuracy, as this was a redundant variable anyways.
  1. Crm.Cd.2(905,717 missing)
  2. Crm.Cd.3(972,168 missing)
  3. Crm.Cd.4(974,413 missing)
  • For the seccond, third, and fourth crime code variables, it is logical to remove them. We are only concerned with the primary crime when predicting severity which is already stored in Crm.Cd. This reasoning, in addition to the fact that these variables have so many missing values suggests that their presence will not add anything meaningful to our model. Lets remove them from our dataset:
LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  select(-Crm.Cd.2,-Crm.Cd.3,-Crm.Cd.4)

Feature Engineering

Introducing the New Variable

As discussed in the introduction, we will be creating a severity variable to provide some insight for police officers and dispatchers to refer to when considering where their attention is most warranted with regards to crimes currently in progress.

To recap, the UCR program created by the FBI assigns offenses a designation of part 1 or part 2, with regards to the severity and frequency of occurrence. More information is collected on part 1 crimes than part 2 crimes and this data is used to guide nationwide law enforcement policy and directives. A Part.1.2 variable is currently included in our dataset to encode each observations designation with regards to the FBI UCR program.

Recall that the scale of the newly proposed severity variable is as follows:

  1. Low Severity (Lowest Severity) - Offenses include minor, non-violent misdemeanors such as vandalism, petty theft, and trespassing.

  2. Moderate Severity - Offenses include more serious misdemeanors and property-related crimes, such as non-violent burglary, grand theft, and identity theft.

  3. High Severity - Offenses include non-lethal violent crimes, such as assault, battery, or unarmed robbery.

  4. Extreme Severity (Highest Severity) - Offenses include serious, violent crimes with a high plausibility of lethality. All sexual crimes will also be classified as severity 4. Examples of offenses include homicide, rape, armed robbery, and aggravated assault.

Now for the heavy lifting!

Appropriately identifying which crimes are of which severity and assigning the corresponding Crm.Code to its respective severity value could prove to be a rather arduous process. Lets make a basic plan of attack, stepwise:

  1. Identify all unique crime codes stored in Crm.Code in LAPDcrimedata
  2. Create a look-up table that encodes key/value pairs between these crime codes and their corresponding severity value
  3. Apply this look-up table to the smaller LA_crime_subset dataset to create a new variable, severity, and assign all observations a value for this variable based on their Crm.Code value.

In case you have not read the attached codebook, Crm.Cd.1 is designated to contain the most severe offense being committed in each instance of crime. For example, if a homicide was in progress and the suspect also happened to be nude in public, Crm.Cd.1 would contain the code for homicide, not public nudity or indecent exposure. One of the subsequent crime code variables, Crm.Cd.2,Crm.Cd.3, or Crm.Cd.4 would contain the indecent exposure code. Furthermore, Crm.Cd.1 and Crm.Cd contain the same value. Although they store the same code, when we ran our summary of the dataset earlier, Crm.Cd.1 had a couple of missing values, while Crm.Cd had zero missing values. As a result, for the creation of the severity variables look-up tables, it seems most appropriate to examine the Crm.Cd variable.

Now that we possess all of the relevant crime codes and their descriptions, we can proceed to creating the look-up table to match crimes to their appropriate severity values. Before we can create the structure of the look-up table itself, we must assign severity levels to each value of Crm.Cd.

Using each crimes description, there is a fairly logical severity value to match it with. Technically, the fact that I am the one designating severity values for each Crm.Cd creates the possibility that I will introduce inaccuracy/bias into the data. I am fully aware of this fact, but I believe that the severity values I have designated fully align with morals held by most of society in the United States. Earlier, I stated that severity values of four are for the worst offenses possible. I have decided that in addition to crimes that have the immediate possibility of a loss of life, severity will also include sexual crimes due to their inherently violent and damaging nature. Additionally, since the goal of the creation of the severity variable is to judge the scope of the worst offense in an instance of crime, it is unnecessary to consider the secondary crime code variables in the designation of severityvalues.

Adressing Date Variables

We already removed the DATE.RPTD variable due to its non-usefulness. There is one date variable left, DATE.OCC which will likely be useful- but first it requires some tinkering!

The DATE.OCC variable is currently stored as a character value that contains a date in a DD/MM/YYYY format. While this information could prove useful to our modeling process, especially since we have data accumlated over the course of four years, it is hard to deal with in its current format. Some possibly useful components of these dates could be:

  1. Year that the crime occurred
  • Since we have four years of data, knowing the year could help predict severity
  1. Month that the crime occurred
  • Certain months of the year may have different frequencies of occurrence of crime or more severe crimes that occur during those months
  1. Day of the week that the crime occurred
  • Different days of the week(especially weekends) could have different frequencies of occurrence of crime or more severe crimes that occur on those days.
  1. Season during which the crime occurred
  • We all know that different seasons come with different emotions and events (dont bring up politics at Thanksgiving!), therefore incorporating a variable that encodes the season during which a crime occurred could help predict severity.

Lets create some new variables to store this possibly useful information for each observation. Once these variables are created, we can remove the original DATE.OCC variable.

LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>%
  mutate(Year.OCC = year(as.Date(DATE.OCC,format="%m/%d/%Y")),
    Month.OCC = month(as.Date(DATE.OCC,format="%m/%d/%Y")),
    Weekday.OCC = wday(as.Date(DATE.OCC,format="%m/%d/%Y"), label = TRUE),
    Season.OCC = case_when(                 
      Month.OCC %in% c(12, 1, 2) ~ "Winter",
      Month.OCC %in% c(3, 4, 5) ~ "Spring",
      Month.OCC %in% c(6, 7, 8) ~ "Summer",
      Month.OCC %in% c(9, 10, 11) ~ "Fall"))

LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  select(-DATE.OCC)

Now, we have four additional variables Year.OCC, Month.Occ, Weekday.OCC, and Season.OCC. We also removed the DATE.OCC variable, as all of its relevant information is encoded in the four new variables that are now a part of the LA_crime_subset dataset. We will discover whether these new variables were actually worth our time to create once we reach the EDA section of this project.

From the above, we can observe that the observations of crimes for which there is no entry for the Vict.Sex and Vict.Descent mostly refer to crimes for which there is not necessarily a clear victim, such as stealing from a vehicle or embezzlement. To handle the missing values of Vict.Sex and Vict.Descent, it seems appropriate to add additional factor levels called No Sex and No Descent and assign the blank entries of both variables to these levels, respectively. While were here, there are also 12 values of Vict.Sex that contain the letter H, which is not a valid gender in this dataset, so we will remove those observations. Lets do it!

#before messing with these variables, we must convert them back to character type, or else we end up with integers stored in them due to ifelse() causing issues when passed a factor variable

LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  mutate(Vict.Sex = ifelse(as.character(Vict.Sex) == "","No Sex",as.character(Vict.Sex))) 

LA_crime_subset<- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  mutate(Vict.Descent = ifelse(as.character(Vict.Descent)=="","No Descent",as.character(Vict.Descent)))

#ensure vict.sex and vict.sex are factors to preserve structure
LA_crime_subset$Vict.Sex <- as.factor(LA_crime_subset$Vict.Sex)

LA_crime_subset$Vict.Descent <- as.factor(LA_crime_subset$Vict.Descent)

#remove H values of vict.sex
LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  filter(as.character(Vict.Sex) != "H")

#drop unused '' levels of both vict.sex and vict.descent
LA_crime_subset$Vict.Sex <- droplevels(LA_crime_subset$Vict.Sex)
LA_crime_subset$Vict.Descent <- droplevels(LA_crime_subset$Vict.Descent)

From the above, we can observe that missing values of Vict.Sex and Vict.Descent have been converted according to the procedure we described.

When examining the victim-less crimes for which there was no Vict.Sex or Vict.Descent, it also became obvious that many of these crimes have the Vict.Age set to 0 to designate missing values. This skews the distribution of age as a numeric variable. Additionally, it should be noted that the current minimum value of Vict.Age is -4, which is physically impossible. Lets proceed by converting Vict.Age values of 0 to NA, and removing observations where the Vict.Age values are less than 0:

#I originally accomplished this task using an ifelse() function within the mutate() function, but this was messing up my dataset horribly, so I had to figure out an alternate approach using case_when()
LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>%
  mutate(Vict.Age = case_when(Vict.Age == 0 ~ NA_real_, Vict.Age >= 0 ~ Vict.Age))

The last missing data we must fix is regarding the Cross.Street variable, for which there are 150,159 missing entries. Since we already have multiple variables that refer to geographical/location information regarding each observation of crime, it is reasonable to remove the Cross.Street variable from our dataset.

LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>%

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Now that our LA_crime_subset subset of the larger LAPDcrimedata dataset has been sufficiently tidied, with relevant preprocessing steps taken, we are ready to begin exploring the underlying structures within the data at hand. To begin this process, we should note that of the original 974,477 observations of crime with 28 variables stored for each observation, we are now left with 184,788 observations with 19 variables - some of which are variables that were created during the feature engineering process

Visualizing the Outcome Variable, Severity

To begin our EDA, it seems most appropriate to examine the very thing we will be attempting to predict, the severity variable. Lets get a visual representation of the distribution of severity in the LA_crime_subset dataset. Observe the following:

LA_crime_subset%>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Severity))+
  geom_bar(fill="skyblue",color="black")+
  geom_text(aes(label=..count..),stat="count",vjust=-0.25)+
  labs(title="Distribution of 'Severity'", x="Severity Value",y="Frequency")

From the above bar chart, we can observe that the distribution of severity is right skewed, with more observations falling into the lower levels of severity, rather than the higher, more serious levels. This is not very surprising, as it is logical that the majority of offenses that occur in Los Angeles, even in its most crime-ridden neighborhoods, are not violent crimes, lethal crimes, felonies, or sexual crimes. We should also note that the most common level of severity is 2, which indicates that property related crimes and misdemeanors happen at a much higher rate than other crimes in these neighborhoods of LA. This checks out, as urban areas with high population density often experience a surplus of various forms of theft and vandalism.

Correlation Plot Amongst Variables

For our next step in the EDA process, it seems logical to proceed with a correlation plot amongst the variables in our dataset to observe the underlying relationships that we may not yet be aware of. This should help us identify which variables will be most relevant for our modeling process going forward. It is only relevant to include a correlation plot amongst numeric variables, or those for which there is an underlying numeric structure that is productive to examine linear relationships with:

The above correlation plot is not extremely useful. We can observe that there are neglibly small relationships amongst almost all of the variables we ran this correlation plot on. The only variables for which we observe a relationship are:

  1. Severity and Weapon.Used => +0.79
  • Severity and Weapon.Used have a strong positive linear relationship. This makes sense, as the use of a weapon during the perpetration of a criminal offense would indicate that the crime being committed is more severe.
  1. Severity and Vict.Age => -0.14
  • Severity and Vict.Age have a very weak negative linear relationship. This indicates very weakly that as Severity increases, victim age decreases. This is mildly surprising to me, as I would hope that the most severe crimes are not committed against the youngest people. It could be rationalized by thinking that most severe crimes are committed against younger people, not necessarily the youngest people, in relation to the amount of severe crimes committed against the elderly.
  1. Weapon.Used and Vict.Age => -0.12
  • Weapon.Used and Vict.Age have a very weak negative correlation. This indicated that when a weapon is used to perpetrate a crime, we expect the victims age to be lower. This relationship is not incredibly strong, so we might want to examine a bar chart later to see if there is a more visually identifiable trend here 4.. LAT and LONG => -1.00
  • The latitude and longitude variables have a perfectly correlated negative linear relationship. This makes sense, as they indicate movement in opposite directions. This relationship does not really provide any meaningful information.

Before we proceed to our categorical variables, I would like to further examine the relationship between Vict.Age and Severity, as I thought that their negative correlation was slightly odd. Let us accomplish this using ggplot2 with geom_histogram() and the structure of a stacked bar chart:

ggplot(LA_crime_subset, aes(x = Vict.Age, fill = Severity)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 3, position = "fill", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Victim's Age  Explained by Severity",
       x = "Victim's Age",
       y = "Proportion",
       fill = "Severity")

From the above we can observe that the negative correlation displayed in the correlation plot for the relationship between Vict.Age and Severity is, in-fact correct. This is likely due to the fact that the majority of crimes against persons under 18 in our dataset were either violent(assault on a minor, child abuse,etc.) or sexual in nature (we designated sexual crimes to always be severity 4). As a result, this relationship makes sense and could mean that Vict.Age will be a good predictor for Severity.

While were here, lets also take a second to examine the Weapon.Used and Vict.Age relation, using a stacked bar chart similar to the above.

Since there was not a meaningful relationship between TIME.OCC and severity when it is considered as a numerical value. Victims Ethnicity and Crime Severity

  • Severity 2 => No clear top 3 (loosely indicates that property crimes tend to happen at a relatively equal rate, regardless of ethnic descent)

Day of the Week and Severity

Lets examine the relationship between which day of the week a crime occurs on and its corresponding severity.

ggplot(LA_crime_subset, aes(x = Weekday.OCC, fill = Severity)) +

The distribution of severity is nearly identical for all days of the week. There is a slight increase in severity 3 and 4 on weekends, which suggest that a crime occurring on a weekend may result in higher probability of it being a worse offense. This suggests that our feature engineering to create day of the week was not particularly useful, as it doesnt provide us with any productive information. Lets correct this by encoding the useful information that we found from this plot into a new variable WEEKEND that is either true or false based on whether the crime occurred on a weekend:

# I use the case_when() function even though this is binary mutation because ifelse() kept affecting other parts of my data when used with mutate() earlier
LA_crime_subset <- LA_crime_subset %>%
  mutate(WEEKEND = case_when(Weekday.OCC %in% c("Mon","Tue","Wed", "Thu", "Fri") ~ 0, Weekday.OCC %in% c("Sat","Sun")~ 1))

LA_crime_subset$WEEKEND <- as.factor(LA_crime_subset$WEEKEND)

Model Set-up

Now that we have a basic idea of which variables will likely prove useful to our model, its time to proceed with the actual modeling process itself. I know, its such a relief! Looking at data for so long can become tedious, especially with data such as this crimes dataset that does not always have an entirely clear structure or embedded relationships throughout.

Splitting the dataset

Before we can proceed to recipe creation and model specifications, we must first split our larger dataset into training and testing sets. The purpose of this is to preserve the integrity of our models through having an untouched set for which we can test models that are trained on the training set on. Having a training and testing set helps us avoid overfitting by evaluating a models performance on unseen data, rather than the training data that it is already familiar with. Additionally, we will not be touching the testing set after its creation, at least until it is time to truly evaluate model performance. We will also only evaluate the models performance on the testing set one singular time. Preserving the untouched nature of the testing set helps prevent data leakage, which occurs when we attempt to wrongly introduce the testing set to our training process with the misguided goal of boosting model performance.

When we split the data into training and testing, we must also ensure that we take extra steps to guarantee that our process is reproducible by specifying a seed before doing so. Lets split the data:

# seed(123) is my personal favorite, it just has a certain ring!
set.seed(123)

#split the data, we use proportion=70/30 training/testing
crimedata_split <- LA_crime_subset %>% 
  initial_split(prop=0.7, strata=Severity)

#store 
crimedata_train <- training(crimedata_split)
crimedata_test <- testing(crimedata_split)

Now, we have a reproducible process that splits our LA_crime_subset data into two datasets, where one is for training and contains 70% of the data while the other contains 30% of the data and will later be used for testing. We have also specified for our split to occur using stratified-sampling with regards to the outcome variable Severity. The use of stratified sampling will ensure that we have equal proportions of the levels of the outcome variable in both our training and testing sets

Specifying the Model Recipe

Now that we have a training set and a testing set, we need a recipe that can be fed into any of the four machine learning models that we will try to apply to the training data. This recipe is generic to any model, which is very useful as it means we do not need to create many different recipes, which could be tedious.

Lets create our recipe while taking into consideration everything we have observed throughout the pre-processing, tidying, and EDA steps so far.

  • Note : W will not be including the Crm.Cd variable as a predictor, since doing so would make the models deterministic as Crm.Cd was directly used to assign Severity values to all observations in the dataset.

  • Additional note: We will not be including the following variables:

  1. Crm.Cd - For the above mentioned reason.
  2. TIME.OCC - We have already stored what seemed to be the relevant take away from the TIME.OCC variable in the Time.Period variable.
  3. AREA - AREA and AREA.NAME encode the same geographical information, so I will keep AREA.NAME as it is easier to interpret.
  4. LOCATION - We already have multiple variables that refer to geographical information, additionally this is a character string coerced into a factor and there are hundreds of unique locations.
  5. Weekday.OCC - We have stored the relevant weekday information in the WEEKEND variable
  6. Month.OCC - did not provide meaningful information regarding severity
  7. Season.OCC - did not provide meaningful information regarding severity
  8. LAT - correlation plot showed 0 relation between LAT and outcome.
  9. LON - correlation plot showed 0 relation between LON and outcome.
  • One Last Note: At this step in the process, we technically still have missing data for the Vict.Age variable. This was discussed during the pre-processing and tidying sections, but seems relevant to mention again before we proceed with recipe creation. Missing values for Vict.Age were originally encoded as 0, which affects the numerical distribution of the age variable. These missing values were for crimes that did not necessarily have a clear victim, not one where the victim was literally an infant in the womb. Therefore, it was appropriate to change these values to NA rather than 0. Additionally, now that we have arrived to our recipe creation step, I will not be imputing Vict.Age values, as this would impose age values on instances where there should not be any.
#Recipe definition, we dummy variable encode all categorical vars:
crime_recipe <- recipe(Severity~ AREA.NAME + Rpt.Dist.No + Part.1.2 + Vict.Age + Vict.Sex + Vict.Descent +Premis.Cd + Weapon.Used+Year.OCC + Time.Period + WEEKEND, data = LA_crime_subset) %>% 
  step_dummy(AREA.NAME) %>% 
  step_dummy(Rpt.Dist.No) %>% 
  step_dummy(Part.1.2) %>% 
  step_dummy(Vict.Sex) %>% 
  step_dummy(Vict.Descent) %>% 
  step_dummy(Premis.Cd) %>% 
  step_dummy(Weapon.Used) %>% 
  step_dummy(Year.OCC) %>% 
  step_dummy(Time.Period) %>% 
  step_naomit(all_predictors(),skip=FALSE) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric_predictors())

Before we proceed to the next steps in our process, we should examine what our training dataset will look like once this recipe is applied. This is extremely relevant, as we had a large amount of categorical predictors.

We are most interested in how many predictors we will have after the dummy encoding process takes place, as this will determine the appropriate choices for our hyperparameters. Additionally, if we have too many predictors in our training dataset after the recipe is applied, our models could take many hours, if not days or longer to tune. Lets do this using the prep and bake functions:

#using lab code, we can do this all in one fell swoop
prelim <- prep(crime_recipe) %>% 
  bake(new_data = crimedata_train)
print(ncol(prelim)-1)
## [1] 1394

From the above, we can see that after our recipe is applied to the training set, we now have 1405 predictors. This is an absurdly large amount and will be computationally impossible for my computer to manage in a reasonable amount of time. It is likely that the Premis.Cd and Rpt.Dist.No variables are the culprits causing our humongous number of predictors. Lets examine how many unique values there are for each of these variables:

unique_premis.cd <- LA_crime_subset %>%
  distinct(Premis.Cd) %>%
  nrow()

  distinct(Rpt.Dist.No) %>%
  nrow()

unique_premis.cd
## [1] 230
unique_rpt.dist.no
## [1] 1113

There are far too many unique values for Rpt.Dist.No and Premis.Cd, this is causing the influx of predictors after our recipe is applied. As a result, I will modify the crime_recipe, so that it does not include Rpt.Dist.No.

#same recipe as before, just without Rpt.Dist.No, and premis.cd
crime_recipe <- recipe(Severity~ AREA.NAME + Part.1.2 + Vict.Age + Vict.Sex + Vict.Descent + Weapon.Used+Year.OCC + Time.Period + WEEKEND, data = LA_crime_subset) %>% 
  step_dummy(AREA.NAME) %>% 
  step_dummy(Part.1.2) %>% 
  step_dummy(Vict.Sex) %>% 
  step_dummy(Vict.Descent) %>% 
  step_dummy(Weapon.Used) %>% 
  step_dummy(Year.OCC) %>% 
  step_dummy(Time.Period) %>%
  step_dummy(WEEKEND) %>% 
  step_naomit(all_predictors(),skip=TRUE) %>% 
  step_center(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_numeric_predictors())

This recipe should now be much more manageable for tuning hyperparameters later on.

Now that we have specified a recipe, there a few more steps we must complete before we are ready to apply this recipe to our prospective models.

Applying K-Fold Cross Validation

K-fold cross-validation is a resampling technique in which we split the training dataset into k equally sized subsets(called folds). Then, we use k-1 of the folds as training data, and the remaining fold as a testing dataset. This process is repeated k times, with each fold being used as the testing dataset one time. We then average the performance metrics collected over each iteration to get a standardized estimate of model performance.

We use k-fold cross-validation, rather than simply comparing our model results on the entire training set, in order to avoid introducing bias/poor performance due to over-fitting into our model. When we compare model results on the entire training set, we may produce deceivingly accurate performance metrics because we are evaluating the performance of our model based on data it is already familiar with, rather than unseen data. When k-fold cross-validation is applied, we simulate unseen data by using k-1 folds for training and the k-th fold for evaluating performance.

In the case of this dataset, we have a decently large number of observations, as well as a fairly large number of predictors. As a result, we may want to steer clear of picking a value for k that is too large. Pairing a large number of folds with a lengthy, highly dimensional dataset can be incredibly computationally intense (intensity that my little HP laptop might struggle to accommodate on a reasonable time frame). As a result, we will use a fairly standard number of folds: k=5.

Lets apply this k=5 cross validation:

# set our seed again, just in case.
set.seed(123)

#Create 5-fold CV object
crime_folds <- vfold_cv(LA_crime_subset, v=5)

Now that we have a 5-fold cross validation object created from our LA_crime_dataset, we can proceed to the actual modeling process.

Building Our Models

Now that we have all of the necessary components, its time to tackle the actual model-building process. Of the models we have examined throughout this course, the ones which seem most appropriate to apply to our data, since it is a multi-class classifcation problem, are:

  1. Elastic Net Logistic Regression
  2. Random Forest
  3. Support Vector Machines (SVMs)
  4. Gradient Boosted Trees

Lets proceed with building these models for the classification problem at hand in sequential order. A general framework for each model shall be:

  1. Define a model specification with a suitable model engine and select classification as the mode.
  2. Add the specification and the crime recipe to a workflow.
  3. Create a tuning grid for any hyperparameter(s) required by each model.
  4. Tune each model using our crime_folds object.

Creating Model Specifications:

Our first step in the process of building and applying models to our data is creating a specification object for each model that sets its engine and mode appropriately. We must do this for all four models individually

#EN logistic regression specifications, we will be tuning penalty().
# ran into an error when tuning, needed to come back and specific multinomial logistic regression, as the default is binomial
#Encountered another error after running family="multinomial", console message suggested using multinom_reg() instead
glm_spec <- multinom_reg(penalty=tune(),mixture=tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet") %>% 
  set_mode("classification") #%>% 
  #set_args(family="multinomial")

#random forest specification, we will be tuning mtry(),trees(), and min_n().
randforest_spec <- rand_forest(mtry=tune(),trees=tune(),min_n=tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("ranger",importance= "impurity") %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

#support vector machine (SVM) specification, we will be tuning cost() and rbf_sigma().
svm_spec <- svm_rbf(cost=tune(),rbf_sigma=tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

#gradient boosted tree, we will be tuning trees(), learn_rate(), and min_n().
gbt_spec <- boost_tree(trees=tune(),learn_rate=tune(),min_n=tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("xgboost") %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

We now have stored objects for each model that specify the model, which hyperparameters we will be tuning, the appropriate model engine, and our desired goal of classification.

Creating Hyperparameter Grids

Earlier, when we created the specification objects for each model, we selected specific hyperparameters for each that will need to be tuned to achieve our best model performance. In order to be able to successfully conduct the tuning process, we will need to create grid objects of possible hyperparameters that will be passed to the tune_grid() function later on.

#create appropriate hyperparameter grid for elastic net logistic regression
#penalty - tune values between 10^-2 and 10
#mixture - tune values between 0 and 1
glm_grid <- grid_regular(
  penalty(range=c(-2,1)),
  mixture(range=c(0,1)),
  levels=4
)


#create appropriate hyperparameter grid for random forest
#mtry - sample between 5 and 20 predictors per split
#trees - employ between 100 and 500 trees
#min_n - tune between 5 and 15 data points per node
randforest_grid<- grid_regular(
  mtry(range=c(5,20)),
  trees(range=c(100,500)),
  min_n(range=c(5,15)),
  levels=5
)

#create appropriate hyperparameter gird for SVM
#cost - tune from 10^-2 to 10
#rbf_sigma - tune from 10^-2 to 10
svm_grid<-grid_regular(
  cost(range=c(-2,1)),
  rbf_sigma(range = c(-2,1)),
  levels=5
)
#create appropriate hyperparameter grid for gradient boosted tree
#trees - employ between 50 and 200 trees in tuning process
#learn_rate - learning rate between 0.05 and 0.1
#tree_depth - between 2 and 6 keeps trees fairly shallow
gbt_grid<-grid_regular(
  trees(range=c(50,200)),
  learn_rate(range=c(0.05,0.1)),
  tree_depth(range=c(2,6))
)

For these hyperparameter grids, I chose values for which there should be a happy medium between minimized run time/computational efficiency and model performance. We will see if these expectations come to pass once the tuning process is complete.
